])(;B[ls]C[This is the perfect timing for this forcing move. Why? Because White cannot cut at A, because then Black will capture 4 stones with B.

So it's a "free" move for Black. This is an advanced idea in fighting where you accept profit as tactical momentum.

But why is M1 a good move? Because White has this weak group in the corner, and White 1 presents a possibility of saving it. So M1 proactively defends against White 1 WHILE attacking White's 4 stones.]LB[kn:A][kr:B][ms:1]TR[nr][oo][oq][or][pn][po][pp][pq]))(;W[lr]C[It's harder to see, but this is a better idea. White is saying "I sacrifice these 2 stones, will you really invest another move for only 5 points?" -- but Black is almost forced to.]TR[nr][or];B[oq];W[mp]C[In this exchange, White is happy. Because he gets nice strength in the center, and his 3 stones are reasonably safe due to Black's shortage of liberties. Black has spent 2 moves for 5 points, which is inefficient by itself, but it's also less than what White got.

What happened in the game was Black 1 - White 3. White stubbornly grasped onto those 2 stones. Then, if Black plays 2, Black will be happy because White is much easier to attack.]SQ[ho]LB[lr:2][mp:4][mr:1][oq:3]TR[po][pp][pq]))(;B[jd]C[When Black plays here, he's making territory in an efficient way, from the 4th-line.

